node.text:
I had a great weekend with my wife (😍) and my parents in Frankenjura (Germany). I haven't been there for a while, and it was great to check out some crags I have never been to before. 

The ticklist is 👇
House of Cards 9a (my suggestion 8c+) in 4 tries in Eibgrat, FA @moritzwelt_climbing in 2020.
One Whore’s Town 8b+ (my suggestion 8b or 8b/b+) onsight in Zauppenberger Wand.
Nice Freshly Baked 9a in 2 tries in Schlaraffenland, FA by @alexandermegos in 2014.
Alexander der Grosse 8c/c+ in 2 tries in Schlaraffenland. Odins Tafel 8b retro-onsight (tried many years ago up to 2nd bolt). Friends Like You 8b/b+ in 3 tries Dr Kimble 8a+ retro-onsight (tried many years ago up to 2nd bolt) Ragnarök 8a onsight 💪

The video features the ascent of Nice Freshly Baked 9a. It is a more complicated exit to the route Shangri-la 8c+, the famous route by Guido Kostermeyer that I repeated when I was 14 years old. Honestly, it was quite unnerving as I was afraid that I would struggle in the lower section. Fortunately, it worked out all right 🙏 I made it pretty solid up to the crux of the right exit. There is a long move off a heel-hook that fit my style perfectly, so it is hard to say for me if it deserves the 9a grade for me as it does not feel that much harder than Shangri-la, but for sure for shorter climbers, it must feel much more desperate 🤔

node.text: 1st place from this year's lead Czech Republic Championship on @lezeckastena.bigwall in Prague. I enjoyed the end of the route - great setting with the biggest dyno I have ever done on a lead wall. It would be pretty easy dyno on a bouldering wall, but 15 meters above the ground, it felt unnerving, for sure. Great climbing by @konecnik who took the silver, @martin.stranik was third.

I had a great weekend with my wife (😍) and my parents in Frankenjura (Germany). I haven't been there for a while, and it was great to check out some crags I have never been to before. 

The ticklist is 👇
House of Cards 9a (my suggestion 8c+) in 4 tries in Eibgrat, FA @moritzwelt_climbing in 2020.
One Whore’s Town 8b+ (my suggestion 8b or 8b/b+) onsight in Zauppenberger Wand.
Nice Freshly Baked 9a in 2 tries in Schlaraffenland, FA by @alexandermegos in 2014.
Alexander der Grosse 8c/c+ in 2 tries in Schlaraffenland. Odins Tafel 8b retro-onsight (tried many years ago up to 2nd bolt). Friends Like You 8b/b+ in 3 tries Dr Kimble 8a+ retro-onsight (tried many years ago up to 2nd bolt) Ragnarök 8a onsight 💪

The video features the ascent of Nice Freshly Baked 9a. It is a more complicated exit to the route Shangri-la 8c+, the famous route by Guido Kostermeyer that I repeated when I was 14 years old. Honestly, it was quite unnerving as I was afraid that I would struggle in the lower section. Fortunately, it worked out all right 🙏 I made it pretty solid up to the crux of the right exit. There is a long move off a heel-hook that fit my style perfectly, so it is hard to say for me if it deserves the 9a grade for me as it does not feel that much harder than Shangri-la, but for sure for shorter climbers, it must feel much more desperate 🤔

Not just a regular protein bar, and definitely not a regular protein source 🦗

As I get older, food is a more and more important part of my training routine. I am always looking out for new nutrition hacks. @sensfoods products were an easy improvement. My team and I liked them. At first, we were just customers. Then we got to know the story and the mission behind it, and we were hooked. You know the rest, I decided to join the company 💪

By the way, I am not the biggest fan of protein bars. I prefer real meals, but this bar is closest to real food when I am travelling or climbing on the rock. What I like even more is just putting pure cricket protein powder in my breakfast bowl 👌 However, I know that many of you might get scared, so that makes the protein bar quite a nice start.

Some of you wrote to me that you tried something from our Sens shop and liked it. That's amazing! Would you like to try a starter pack of all Sens products?

Write to me below this post in the comments about why you think cricket protein can make sens-e. In 10 DAYS - (by September 22), we choose with @sensfoods 20 of you who will get the starter pack❗

Find out more at www.eatsens.com - the link in BIO.

node.text:
WOW, that was @rockmasterfestival 🇮🇹

After a one-year break, we met with other friends from all over Europe (including @martin.stranik and @ella_adamovska ) in my favorite Arco, near Lago di Garda ⛰️ Rock Master is a competition with the longest history in sport climbing. I dreamed about this competition since I was a little boy. It's just that kind of event that every climber wants to be a part of 🙏

This year's combination of KO boulder and lead duel gave rise to so many great emotions. I think that route setters managed to set interesting boulder problems and a challenging lead route 🤔 Anyway, the climbers and spectators had a lot of fun until late in the evening. 

In the KO boulder, I won thanks to topping 2 boulder problems, 1 and 4! In the lead duel, after a very close defeat in the semifinal with @michael.piccolruaz , I ended 3rd. The lead duel was eventually won by @steghiso 👏 After adding up the results from KO boulder and lead duel, I took the 6th trophy from Rock Master home. It's a great honor for me. 

Among the women, it ended up in a tie between @vitalukan and @jessy_pilz

Check out the first of the 2 videos from the Rock Master. This awesome video is all about the racing, great vibes, and exciting duels. The link is in BIO (the first in the Link Beta) 👌

node.text:
Is chipping routes right or wrong? 🤔

Nature is the most superior route setter and I believe that even for contemporary route setters in the climbing gyms, nature is the source of their primary inspiration. But just like route setters in the gym, nature doesn’t always do the best possible job ⛰ Well, better said, the possible job from a climber's point of view. Some pieces of rock happen to have no holds at all, some happen to have possibly too many holds. Some rock is too sharp, some rock is too crumbly. 

If you have been climbing for a while, you must know that modification of the rock exists. It actually exists for as long as climbing exists. Getting to the top of the mountain or tower by any means, even though it meant altering the rock, cannot be that surprising. I would like to 💪 focus in this article on chipping, manufacturing, and reinforcing the rock in sport climbing.

Read the full article on the website 👉 the link is in BIO (www.adamondra.com/updates)

3rd place in Duel, 1st in combined in Rock Master 2021 👌

So the duel was definitely a little different because it was done after practice, the route was harder and it was much more about dealing with the energy and the pump ✊ So I think it was a little bit closer to the actual climbing. But in the end, I was not really expecting that we will climb faster under 1:10 and our fastest time was 1:07 in the semifinals with @michael.piccolruaz. But it was very close, but in the end, Mischa proceeded to the finals and I went on to race for the 3rd place with @yannick_flohe. That felt pretty desperate for me, my right arm was so pumped as it was the fastest to clip off the right hand for most of the clips. But I had just enough in the tank for third place.

But this year the Rock Master is the combination of boulder and duel. And thanks to first place in boulder and third place in duel I won the @rockmasterfestival for the 6th time!

Pics by @pet.phot

1st place in Rock Master Festival Boulder! 🇮🇹

After yesterday’s practice, I think that the route setters thought that the boulders are way too easy, and they made all the boulder problems, except for the last one, significantly harder 🤯 The first one being physically turned into super physical. The boulder number two was changed with almost every hold and foothold being slightly worse that made the top almost impossible. Number three was a slab, and we barely did a move. But the number fourth was just the same as during practice, I did just on the limit, and it was incredible to top it out on my first try, being the only climber to do so and taking first place. I am happy for @martin.stranik, who took second place 💪

The first day of the @rockmasterfestival - a common practice of 4 competition boulderproblems. Tomorrow only 3 tries for each problem. 

The Rock Master is a unique competition in many ways, but one of the differences is that you have some time to practice. So today was the practice day. We have practised 4 boulder problems and duel route. And, actually, it was 1-hour of practice boulderproblems and a 1-hour training duel route which was quite tiring. On duel route, we hade twice 6 minutes and within due those 6 minutes we could do whatever we wanted, so in the second 6 minutes time frame I actually I climbed route twice, and It was quite exhausting. But I definitely really looking forward to the competition.
